            <div class="ins_notes">
                <span class="note" id="note-1"><a href="#ref-1">[1]</a> On the origins of the “association (<i>synodos</i>) of artists (<i>technitai</i>) of Dionysos at Athens” (τῶν περὶ τὸν Διόνυσον τεχνιτῶν τῶν ἐν Ἀθήναις) see Le Guen, vol. 2, 5-14, and most recently, B. Fauconnier, <i>Athletes and Artists in the Roman Empire</i>, 2023, 19-22. The earliest evidence for them is in a decree of the League of the <a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/540726">Delphian</a> Amphiktyony, 279-277 BC, confirming their privileges, <i>F. Delphes</i> III 2, 68, ll. 61-94 = <i>CID</i> 4.12 = Le Guen TE 2. This is the only decree of the association datable to the 3rd cent. BC. In it they honour two officers of the association (<i>hieropoioi</i>), a tragic actor and a singer. It was discovered in the excavations of the Dipylon, at the apparent location of the association’s <i>temenos</i>. Documentary evidence for the Athenian association is collected by Le Guen vol. 1, pp. 57-127, TE 2-TE 16, tabulated pp. 18-22. For the latest decree of the association see <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IEleus/271"><i>I Eleus.</i> 271</a>. For the “world-wide itinerant association of theatrical artists of Dionysos” at Athens in the 2nd cent. AD see <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/AIUK43A/9"><i>AIUK</i> 4.3A, no. 9</a>.</span> 
<span class="note" id="note-2"><a href="#ref-2">[2]</a> This is a work of Tracy’s “Cutter of <i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 1706”, who was active ca. 229/8-203 BC. Sositheos the tragic actor is identifiable with Sostheos II, mentioned as victor at the Lenaia on the Victors’ List, <i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 2325, l. 313 (2325H col. VII, l. 116 in B. W. Millis and S. D. Olson, <i>Inscriptional Records for the Dramatic Festivals in Athens</i>, 2012, p. 221; Stephanis, <i>Dionysiakoi Technitai</i>, 1988, no. 2345; Traill, <i>PAA</i> 861440. “II” might alternatively signify that there were two distinct victorious actors of this name, cf. Le Guen). The Poseidippos in whose dedication the stele is to be placed (16-17) is usually identified as the comic poet of that name, son of Kyniskos of <a class="highlight" href="https://pleiades.stoa.org/places/491701">Kassandreia</a>, who is said by the Suda (π 2111) to have produced his first play two years after the death of Menander, i.e. 291/0 BC (<i>PCG</i> 7 p. 561, Millis and Olson p. 169 on <i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 2325C, l. 80, Traill, <i>PAA</i> 785245).</span>
            </div>
            

